Packages

Code 
library(tidyverse)
library(RColorBrewer)

Data Set

Code 
avocado <- read_csv(here::here("Labs", "Lab 4", "avocado.csv"))

The data set represents the Avocado consumption around the United States from 2013 to 2018. The data set gives us information on the average price and quantity sold across multiple factors: US region, avocado size, type (conventional or organic), and date. The collectors of the data assume that the vast consumption of avocado may be able to explain why younger people are not able to buy homes.

Cleaning The Data Set

Code 
avocado <- avocado |> rename(smallHaas = `4046`, largeHaas = `4225`, xlHaas = `4770`)

# make a data set of unwanted regions
state_minor <- tibble(region = c("California", "GreatLakes", "Midsouth",
                                 "NorthernNewEngland", "Plains" ,"SouthCarolina", 
                                 "SouthCentral", "Southeast", "TotalUS"))

# make a data set of only the major regions
major_regions <- tibble(region = c("West", "Midwest", "Northeast", "South"))

# semi-join so that it contains only observations with the major regions
avocadoMajor <- avocado |> semi_join(major_regions, by = "region" )

# anti-join twice to remove the observations with matches from unwated and major regions
avocadoMetro <- avocado |> anti_join(state_minor, by = "region") |> 
  anti_join(major_regions, by = "region")

Summarizing

Question 3

Code 
avocadoMajor |> filter(year == 2017, type == "organic") |> group_by(region) |> 
  summarise(regionTotal = sum(smallHaas)) |> slice_max(region)
# A tibble: 1 Ã 2
  region regionTotal
  <chr>        <dbl>
1 West      1870206.

Discussion

The West Coast Region sold a total of 1,870,206 organic small Haas avocados in 2017 which is the largest amount out of all the other major regions recorded in this data set.

Question 4

Code 
avocadoMajor |> separate(col = Date, into = c("Year", "Month", "Day"), sep = "-") |> 
  group_by(Month) |> 
  summarise(monthTotalVolume = sum(`Total Volume`), 
            meanTotalVolume = mean(`Total Volume`)) |>
  slice_max(meanTotalVolume)
# A tibble: 1 Ã 3
  Month monthTotalVolume meanTotalVolume
  <chr>            <dbl>           <dbl>
1 02          203427698.        3178558.

Discussion

When the amount of avocados sold per month were totaled across the three years, we find that the month of January sold the most. However, when we look at the average number of avocados sold per month across 2015, 2016, and 2017, we find that the month of February sells the most on average.

Question 5

Code 
metroSummary <- avocadoMetro |> select(`Total Volume`, region) |> 
  group_by(region) |> summarise(sumTotalVol = sum(`Total Volume`),
                                meanTotalVol = mean(`Total Volume`)) |> 
  slice_max(meanTotalVol, n = 5)

top5 <- avocadoMetro |> semi_join(metroSummary, by = "region")

# changing the limits source: https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/lims.html
# color palette: https://statisticsglobe.com/scale-colour-fill-brewer-rcolorbrewer-package-r
ggplot(data = top5, mapping = aes(y = region, x = `Total Volume`, fill = region)) +
  geom_boxplot(size = 0.3) + 
  labs(x = "Total Volume Sold/Week", 
       y = "US City", 
       title = "Total Volume of Avocados Sold Across Top 5 Selling Cities in the USA",
       fill = "City") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", 
                                  size = 13),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 10, 
                                  face = "bold"),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 8), 
        legend.position = "none") + 
  theme_light() + scale_fill_brewer(palette = "RdYlBu")

Discussion

Los Angeles scored highest for Total Volume of avocados sold, with a total volume of 507,896,548 in the three year time frame. The Boxplot also tells us that Los Angeles scores highest in the mean total volume, selling an average of nearly a million each week.

Reshaping

Question 6

Code 
# means
californiaAvocado <- avocadoMetro |> filter(region %in% c("LosAngeles", "SanDiego",
                                                          "Sacramento", "SanFrancisco")) |> 
  select(Date, type, region, AveragePrice) |>
  pivot_wider(names_from = type, values_from = AveragePrice) |>
  group_by(region) |> 
  summarise(meanConventional = mean(conventional), meanOrganic = mean(organic))
# difference in means
summaryCal <- californiaAvocado |> 
  summarise(region = region, meanDiff = abs(meanConventional - meanOrganic))

# plot, source:https://www.learnbyexample.org/r-bar-plot-ggplot2/
californiaAvocado |> pivot_longer(meanConventional:meanOrganic, 
                                  names_to = "type", values_to = "price") |>
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = region, y = price, fill = type)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = position_dodge(), width = 0.6) +
  labs(x = "California City", 
       y = "Avocado Price ($)", 
       title = "Average Price of Conventional and Organic Avocados Across California Cities", 
       fill = "Avocado Type") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", 
                                  size = 15),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 10, 
                                  face = "bold"),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 8), 
        legend.title = element_text(size = 10,
                                    face = "bold"),
        legend.text = element_text(size = 8),
        legend.key.size = unit(.5, "cm")) + 
  scale_fill_discrete(labels = c("Conventional", "Organic")) +
  theme_light()

Discussion

After computing the average price for both conventional and organic avocados across the different California cities, and calculating the differences of their means, we can see that San Francisco has the biggest difference in price between the two types. The average price for a conventional avocado in San Francisco is approximately $1.40 while organic avocados cost $2.20.

Question 7

Code 
myPalette <- c("#80C9F9", "#196BA0", "#A5F980")

avocadoMetro |>
  filter(region %in% c("LosAngeles", "SanDiego", 
                       "Sacramento", "SanFrancisco")) |>
  select(smallHaas:xlHaas, type, region) |> 
  pivot_longer(smallHaas:xlHaas, names_to = "Size", values_to = "Quantity") |>
 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = region, 
                       y = Quantity, 
                       fill = Size)) + 
  geom_col(position = "fill") +
  labs(x = "Region of CA", 
       y = "Proportion of Mean Avocados Sold") +
  facet_grid(~type) + 
  scale_x_discrete(guide = guide_axis(n.dodge = 2)) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = myPalette)

## Data Set

```{r}
avocado <- read_csv(here::here("Labs", "Lab 4", "avocado.csv"))
```

The data set represents the Avocado consumption around the United States from 2013 to 2018. The data set gives us information on the average price and quantity sold across multiple factors: US region, avocado size, type (conventional or organic), and date. The collectors of the data assume that the vast consumption of avocado may be able to explain why younger people are not able to buy homes.

## Cleaning The Data Set

```{r}
avocado <- avocado |> rename(smallHaas = `4046`, largeHaas = `4225`, xlHaas = `4770`)

# make a data set of unwanted regions
state_minor <- tibble(region = c("California", "GreatLakes", "Midsouth",
                                 "NorthernNewEngland", "Plains" ,"SouthCarolina", 
                                 "SouthCentral", "Southeast", "TotalUS"))

# make a data set of only the major regions
major_regions <- tibble(region = c("West", "Midwest", "Northeast", "South"))

# semi-join so that it contains only observations with the major regions
avocadoMajor <- avocado |> semi_join(major_regions, by = "region" )

# anti-join twice to remove the observations with matches from unwated and major regions
avocadoMetro <- avocado |> anti_join(state_minor, by = "region") |> 
  anti_join(major_regions, by = "region")
```
